[5] Cholera - Nepal (Kathmandu)
Date: Thu 27 Jul 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Rising Nepal [edited]
<http://www.gorkhapatra.org.np/content.php?nid=5030>

With the influx of diarrhea patients in various hospitals of the
Capital city, some of the hospitals even detected cholera bacteria
among some of the patients recently. Caused by lack of clean and
uncontaminated drinking water during the time of rainy season, a
large number of people fall victim to the diarrhea and cholera
bacteria every year.
According to information provided by the Kanti Children's Hospital,
the number of diarrhea patients has surged in the month of Shrawan
(July/August) in 2006 as well, of which 3 patients were detected with
the cholera bacterium on 16, 24, and 25 Jul 2006.
The hospital is witnessing some 14 to 15 children being admitted with
gastroenteritis everyday. The department of gastroenteritis at the
hospital today [27 Jul 2006] forwarded stool samples of 3 patients
for laboratory testing among the patients admitted in the hospital
who displayed symptoms of cholera. There have been no cases of death
caused by diarrhea and cholera reported this year [2006].
Meanwhile, Teku Hospital is witnessing a maximum number of patients
suffering from diarrhea these days, but Director of the Hospital Dr.
Kokila Shrestha stated that none of the patients have been diagnosed
with cholera so far. More than 50 patients suffering from diarrhea
are coming to the hospital for treatment everyday. The hospital
record revealed that 7 cases of cholera were diagnosed among the
patients who were treated by the hospital in 2005.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The Kathmandu area can be seen on this map of Nepal:
<http://ncthakur.itgo.com/map04.htm>,
marked as KTM in the Central Region, quite close to Kavre Palanchok. - Mod. LL]
